    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Well-Traveled State</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Ari S Heckman on Nov 13 article on culinary traditions of Rhode Island</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As a proud (and perhaps overzealous) lifelong Rhode Islander, I would like to defend myself and my state. While it is one thing to expose the world to our culinary traditions, it is quite another to portray Rhode Islanders as provincial homebodies. The sophisticated ambitions of many Rhode Islanders seem to pale in comparison to Mr. Lukas's conclusion that we partake in hot-dog banquets with friends from our street.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>As a proud (and perhaps overzealous) lifelong Rhode Islander, I would like to defend myself and my state. While it is one thing to expose the world to our culinary traditions, it is quite another to portray Rhode Islanders as provincial homebodies. The sophisticated ambitions of many Rhode Islanders seem to pale in comparison to Mr. Lukas's conclusion that we partake in hot-dog banquets with friends from our street.</p>
        <p>To be honest, most of my Rhode Island acquaintances haven't even tried a johnnycake. Please let the world know that for better or worse, some of us make it out of Rhode Island. We still appreciate our state, we just disapprove of yet another pigeonhole.</p>
        <p>ARI S. HECKMAN  Providence, R.I.</p>
      </block>
